<ns6105:section xmlns:ns6105="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.shell.scripting.variables.variables">

  <ns6106:title xmlns:ns6106="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Shell variables</ns6106:title>
  <ns6107:para xmlns:ns6107="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    A variable is a name given to a specific value. The variable name is thus a place holder
    for a value which is set somewhere else. Like in command shells themselves, variables 
    within a shell script can be accessed via
    <ns6108:cmdsynopsis xmlns:ns6108="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns6109:command xmlns:ns6109="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
$variableName    
    </ns6109:command></ns6108:cmdsynopsis>
  </ns6107:para>
  <ns6110:para xmlns:ns6110="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Linux shells suppport two types of variables, <ns6111:emphasis xmlns:ns6111="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">system variables</ns6111:emphasis>
    and <ns6112:emphasis xmlns:ns6112="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">user-defined variables</ns6112:emphasis>.
  </ns6110:para>
  
